<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="64" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,535]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,326,331,356]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">Comment.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[332,532,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Melitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnifica">
<emphasis box="[332,532,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">
<collectingCountry box="[332,413,332,356]" name="Malta" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">Melitta</collectingCountry>
magnifica
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[870,986,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Melitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ezoana">
<emphasis box="[870,986,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">M. ezoana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1040,1162,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Melitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sibirica">
<emphasis box="[1040,1162,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">M. sibirica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but 
<taxonomicName box="[1211,1359,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Melitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnifica">
<emphasis box="[1211,1359,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">M. magnifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows reddish cuticule like some other melittid bees [
<emphasis box="[677,932,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">
e.g. 
<taxonomicName box="[725,932,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Dasypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="visnaga">Dasypoda visnaga</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[988,1112,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Dasypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="riftensis">
<emphasis box="[988,1112,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">D. riftensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; Michez 
<emphasis box="[1218,1275,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1282,1341,367,391]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" value="2004.0">2004</number>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Michez" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" refString="Michez, D. &amp; Pauly, A. (2012) A new species of the palaearctic genus Dasypoda Latreille 1802 (Hymenoptera: Dasypodaidae) from the Great Rift Valley in Ethiopia. Zootaxa, 3181, 63 - 68." type="journal article" year="2012">
Michez &amp; Pauly 
<number box="[256,315,404,428]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" value="2012.0">2012</number>
</bibRefCitation>
] and non-melittid bees [
<emphasis box="[600,640,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">e.g.</emphasis>
species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[819,1044,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="squamosus">
<emphasis box="[819,1044,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">Colletes squamosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group (Kuhlmann unpublished data)] living in xeric environments. This presumed adaptation to xeric environments distinguishes 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Melitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">M. magnifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName box="[282,398,477,500]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Melitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ezoana">
<emphasis box="[282,398,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">M. ezoana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[452,573,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Melitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sibirica">
<emphasis box="[452,573,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">M. sibirica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which occur in temperate ecosystem (
<bibRefCitation author="Yasumatsu" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" refString="Yasumatsu, K. &amp; Hirashima, Y. (1956) Discoveries of the genera Macropis Klug and Melitta Kirby in Japan (Hymenoptera, Melittidae). Kontyu, 24, 247 - 255." type="journal article" year="1956">
Yasumatsu &amp; Hirashima 
<number box="[1282,1341,476,500]" pageId="7" pageNumber="64" value="1956.0">1956</number>
; Michez &amp; 
<collectingCountry box="[180,213,512,535]" name="South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands" pageId="7" pageNumber="64">De</collectingCountry>
Meulemeester unpublished data
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
